elements.Text: This document has been created to demo tagging lists, artifacts, tables, links, and images, and is not meant to address all the requirements needed for a PDF to be compliant with WCAG 2.1 or ISO 14289-1 (PDF/UA-1). Please independently review or seek independent counsel to review and identify the relevant requirements of accessibility standards that may apply in your use case.

According to the PDF/UA ISO standard, content that does not represent meaningful content, or appears as a background, shall be tagged as an arŁfact. Examples of such content include decoraŁve images or line spaces.
AddiŁonally, because they are not considered real content, arŁfacts are not present in the structure tree (or in Adobe Acrobat’s Tag Tree).

One common error in a Word document is to use blank lines to create space between paragraphs instead of using paragraph spacing. This may create the desired visual eﬀect but, unless the blank line is tagged as an ar�fact, it may be read by the screen reader as “blank line”.

Another element that the author may decide to tag as an arŁfact is an image that has a capŁon. ParŁcularly if the capŁon contains all the relevant informaŁon about the image in context in the document. Adding alt text to this image would create redundant informaŁon for the screen reader and not tagging it as an arŁfact may confuse the user as the screen reader will indicate “image” but with not associated alt text.

It is possible when authoring tables in Word to indicate the column and row headers for simple tables. Depending upon the method of conversion the correct <TH> tag (table header) may be generated. However there is likely manual clean up to do for table accessibility, parŁcularly for more complex tables.
Vehicles Sold by Model and Color
There are three ways in which links are indicated within a document. Using the full URL, using an abbreviated URL, and embedding the link the text of the document (preferred).

Each approach presents unique challenges in making a PDF accessible to the screen reader user. Embedding the link in the text of the document is the best approach as it provides the most readable and understandable form of the link. The following sentences demonstrate three ways to add a hyperlink to a document:
Check out our for more informaŁon about accessibility at Adobe.
For more informaŁon on accessibility at Adobe click on the link, .
Go to for more informaŁon Adobe accessibility.
A correctly tagged link has the <Link> tag, text associated with the link, and a Link – OBJR tag (the order of the last two is irrelevant.
